[In the past 24 hours, the tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in South Korea has increased by 47 cases and 3 deaths as compared with yesterday's 24 hour period (4-5 Apr 2020) when there were 81 newly confirmed cases. A total of 10 284 confirmed cases, including 186 deaths were reported today, up from 10 237 cases and 183 deaths yesterday [4 Apr 2020]. The daily newly confirmed case count has been at or below 100 for 13 consecutive days and for the 1st time since before 17 Mar 2020 when the daily newly confirmed number was less than 50. Daegu continues to stand out as a focal point for transmission with 65.9% of the total cases reported followed by Gyeongbuk with 12.8% of the total cases reported. In the past 24 hours, Daegu reported 27.7% of the total newly confirmed cases while Seoul represented 23.4% of the newly confirmed cases, and Gyeonggi represented 17.0%. Quarantined imported cases represented 14.9% of the newly confirmed cases. 9 provinces reported 0 newly confirmed cases.

As seen in China, Korea is identifying increasing numbers of imported cases returning to South Korea. There are now 310 imported cases in quarantine with the 1st report of patients in quarantine on 16 Mar 2020, when 4 cases were reported (COVID-19 update (41): global, surge capacity, vaccine development, WHO 20200316.7096222). Overall, there have been a total of 741 imported cases into South Korea, with 50.2% of these cases coming from Europe and 35.6% coming from America. This includes all imported cases since the virus was identified and not just those in quarantine. Also as in China, there is strict surveillance and follow-up of these individuals, reversing the pattern of the western countries strengthening screenings of individuals from South Korea and China. There are obvious concerns regarding initiating new clusters that might escape into the community.

A map of South Korea showing provinces can be seen at https://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/korea-south-administrative-map.htm and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7189083,195. - Mod.MPP]

