[The tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Italy is now 128 948 cases, including 15 887 deaths, up from 124 632 cases and 15 362 deaths reported on 3 Apr 2020. The 24-hour change between 4 and 5 Apr 2020 was 4316 newly confirmed cases, compared with 4805 newly confirmed cases between 2 Apr 2020 and 3 Apr 2020, stable from yesterday's observations. Cases continue to be concentrated in the northern part of the country -- in Lombardy (50 455), the epicenter of the outbreak, Emilia-Romagna (17 089), Veneto (11 226), and Piedmont (12 362). These 4 provinces combined account for 68.1%% of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours. Piedmont, with 15.1% of the newly confirmed cases reported, is seeing more activity than Veneto. There is an excellent interactive map at http://opendatadpc.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/b0c68bce2cce478eaac82fe38d4138b1 to visualize the caseloads per region in near real time.

Today's news is a cautious ray of sunshine with respect to the epicenter of the outbreak in Italy. The reduction in mortality and the health infrastructure able to manage the daily caseloads with decreasing ICU admissions is heartening. But there is definitely concern re: Piedmont and the increase in case reporting.

On 9 Mar 2020, Italy announced a lockdown for the northern provinces where the outbreak was concentrated. On 10 Mar 2020, this was expanded to be countrywide. On 11 Mar 2020, Italy announced the closure of non-essential businesses. It is now 24 days since the start of the lockdown in the north and 22 days since the countrywide lockdown. There does appear to be a positive trend of decreasing daily newly reported cases and mortality, still with small hiccups occasionally.

A map of Italy showing regions can be seen at https://www.mapsofworld.com/italy/regions.html and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7189083,75. - Mod.MPP]

